metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #104
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: Hyper Pixel #118
metadata.description:
Somewhere between pixel-art and axonometric architectural projections, spatial compositions assembled from multi-resolution pixel precise fragments. 

Hyper Pixel is the result of a continued interest in using projections to represent three dimensional object in  two dimensional picture image, and embracing the fact that all digital images are two dimensional arrays of discrete pixels. In that sense it is also a reaction against both skeuomorphism, or mimicking older media in digital form, and the push towards ever increasing fidelity and resolution. The project uses Military perspective, a form of oblique projection, or 45¬∞ - 45¬∞ axonometric projection, because these angels can approximated fittingly by square pixel grid. 

Press s, m, l, x for exporting an image with increasing resolution.
Press p for pause.
Press r for refresh.

Made with P5.js by @introspect0r

metadata.name: Radiant #240
metadata.description:
We were all born with a jewel in our heart ‚Äì golden, shining.  Maybe you call it love, or the divine, or beauty.  The trials of life can cover up that jewel, and make it hard to see the beauty within.  We think we‚Äôre not worthy, not lovable.  But that‚Äôs a lie.  The jewel is always there.  You just need to clean off the gunk.  We are all made of love and supernovas.  You always were, and always will be - radiant.

Radiant was created generatively in p5.js.  Seven possible radial designs overlap on two canvases. On the top canvas, circles or arcs are erased to reveal the canvas below. There are four ways the background gets created, mostly using Perlin noise to pick colors from the palette. There are 34 hand-crafted palettes of 7 colors each. 

Original pixel density 1 with grain added automatically.
After pressing ‚Äúopen‚Äù:
2 ‚Äì 5 to increase pixel density.  
g to add grain.  Adding grain takes a while at pixel density 5.
s to save a png.
Screen resize renders at pixel density 1.

I love sharing what I‚Äôve learned about gen art and inspiring others on my YouTube channel, Steve‚Äôs Makerspace. Follow me there and on Twitter @stevemakerspace and Mastodon @stevesmakerspace.

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #218
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #60
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to save the original Part, pure and untouched.
